  "narrative": "<h3 class=\"story-subheading\">Short impact summary</h3>\n<p class=\"story-text\">Margaret Buck's <em>Renewing the Church-State Partnership for Catholic Education</em> (Peter Lang Verlag, 2020) occupies a specialist niche at the intersection of theology, law, and public administration, drawing measured but steady scholarly attention since its publication. With three recorded citations and availability through retail and library channels, the book has established a modest but durable footprint in the academic conversation around faith-based schooling and its legal and political frameworks.</p>\n\n<h3 class=\"story-subheading\">Full narrative</h3>\n<p class=\"story-text\">Published in 2020, Buck's monograph addresses the enduring and often contested relationship between the Catholic Church and the state in the governance and funding of Catholic schools. Spanning political science, public administration, sociology, theology, and law, the work engages a genuinely interdisciplinary problem \u2014 how longstanding institutional partnerships between religious bodies and secular governments can be renegotiated and sustained in contemporary pluralist societies. This breadth of disciplinary reach is reflected in the conceptual profile attached to the work, which spans governance, partnership theory, and philosophical questions about the role of faith in public education.</p>\n\n<p class=\"story-text\">The book's citation record, while numerically small at three citing works, shows a pattern of sustained and thematically coherent uptake. Citations appeared in 2020, 2022, and 2025, indicating that the work has not faded quickly from view. The citing scholarship \u2014 including a peer-reviewed article in the <em>Journal of Religious Education</em>, a book chapter on school leadership and market dynamics, and a contribution to a volume on Catholic education globally \u2014 reflects engagement from researchers working on religious education policy, institutional ethos, and the governance of faith schools in the United Kingdom. All three citing authors are affiliated with UK institutions, most notably St Mary's University Twickenham London and the University of Glasgow, suggesting the book resonates most immediately within the British Catholic education research community.</p>\n\n<p class=\"story-text\">In terms of broader reach, the book is listed on commercial platforms including Amazon and Goodreads, and holds four library holdings recorded through Open Library, confirming it has entered at least some institutional collections. Its citation percentile places it in roughly the top quarter of comparable works in its cohort \u2014 a meaningful signal given the typically low citation volumes characteristic of specialist monographs in religious education and church-state studies. All three citations have been recorded as mentioning the work, consistent with genuine scholarly engagement rather than purely formal reference.</p>\n\n<p class=\"story-text\">Overall, <em>Renewing the Church-State Partnership for Catholic Education</em> represents a focused scholarly contribution to an ongoing policy-relevant debate. Its reception, concentrated among UK-based education researchers and appearing across a span of five years, suggests the work continues to serve as a reference point for those examining how Catholic schools navigate questions of institutional identity, regulatory scrutiny, and public accountability in a changing political landscape. Further uptake beyond the UK context would strengthen its broader impact claim, but within its specialist domain the book has achieved a credible and continuing presence.</p>",
